## 📋 Project overview

**"A native scheduler for perfect personal time management"**

**Day Planner** is a timetable-based scheduler built to maximize personal time management. Despite being my first Swift and SwiftUI project, it goes well beyond simple task management — implementing **iOS and macOS (status bar app) support**, **Apple Shortcuts-based Focus Mode automation**, and **real-time cross-device sync via CloudKit**.

I started development to solve clear personal needs that existing apps couldn't meet: having **Focus Mode turn on automatically** based on my schedule, and checking current progress and **remaining time at a glance from the Mac Menu Bar**.

<ProjectTechStack techStack={metadata.techStack} {locale} />

## ⚙️ Key work

<ProjectAchievements achievements={[
  {
    tag: 'Platform',
    accent: true,
    title: 'Mac Menu Bar integration with real-time state engine',
    detail: `Built the native <strong>Menu Bar Extra view</strong> for macOS (<code>MenuBarContentView</code>). A <code>Timer</code> inside the global <code>ScheduleStore</code> compares the current time against the schedule <strong>every 30 seconds</strong> — identifying the active event, calculating time remaining, and pushing updates instantly to the status bar and widgets.`
  },
  {
    tag: 'Automation',
    accent: true,
    title: 'Focus Mode automation via Apple Shortcuts',
    detail: `Schedule transitions control the system environment automatically. Beyond <code>UNUserNotificationCenter</code> notifications, the app integrates the <strong>Apple Shortcuts system</strong> and deep links (<code>shortcuts://run-shortcut?name=...</code>). When a schedule starts, the app calls a specified shortcut in the background or foreground — <strong>Work Focus Mode turns on without the user touching settings</strong>.`
  },
  {
    tag: 'Performance',
    title: 'Dynamic repeat schedule engine',
    detail: `Storing daily/weekly/monthly recurrences as thousands of DB records is wasteful. The <strong>OccurrenceService</strong> engine stores only the recurrence rule (<code>RepeatRule</code>) as source data and <strong>computes virtual instances at runtime</strong> for whichever date the user views. This saves disk space significantly while still supporting per-date exception edits and deletions.`
  },
  {
    tag: 'Sync',
    title: 'Reliable real-time sync with CloudKit',
    detail: `A CloudKit sync layer lets schedules created on iPhone flow seamlessly to Mac and back.<ul><li><strong>Debounce (600ms):</strong> Batches rapid user edits to avoid server overload.</li><li><strong>Last-Write-Wins:</strong> Timestamp-based merge in <code>ScheduleRepository</code> prevents data loss on simultaneous edits across devices.</li></ul>`
  },
  {
    tag: 'UI',
    title: 'Lane allocation algorithm for the timeline view',
    detail: `The vertical timeline is the app's core view. When events overlap, a naive layout renders them on top of each other. <strong>TimelineLayoutHelper</strong> analyzes overlapping groups and <strong>dynamically calculates lanes, widths, and offsets</strong> — producing a readable timeline even with dense, overlapping schedules.`
  },
]} />

## 💭 Retrospective

Swift and SwiftUI's declarative model involved a steep learning curve for a first-time project, but forcing me to design from first principles made the architecture cleaner than it might otherwise have been.

The most rewarding part was going beyond a CRUD app — deeply using Apple's ecosystem (CloudKit, Shortcuts, Menu Bar Extra) to build something that actually interacts with the system. Completing a product that solves a real personal workflow problem from scratch made the effort worthwhile.
